 felt like a real journey through different eras, production styles, and em=
otional weights.</p><p data-path-to-node=3D"1">What I loved most about this=
 lineup was the contrast. You had us jumping from the soaring, flawless pop=
 precision of <b data-path-to-node=3D"1" data-index-in-node=3D"117">ABBA</b=
> ("Dancing Queen") and the powerhouse anthems of <b data-path-to-node=3D"1=
" data-index-in-node=3D"170">Adele</b> and <b data-path-to-node=3D"1" data-=
index-in-node=3D"180">Linkin Park</b>, right into these incredibly atmosphe=
ric, deeply poetic, and moody spaces.</p><p data-path-to-node=3D"2">The mid=
-to-late '90s selection in the second half was where the real grit of the g=
ame showed up. Tracks like <b data-path-to-node=3D"2" data-index-in-node=3D=
"109">Radiohead's</b> "Fake Plastic Trees" and <b data-path-to-node=3D"2" d=
ata-index-in-node=3D"146">Tori Amos's</b> "Spark" rely so heavily on distin=
ct, striking metaphors (like a "cracked polystyrene man" or "holding back a=
 glacier") rather than typical pop rhymes. Missing "Spark" because I crosse=
d it with "Crucify"=E2=80=94and missing the beautiful stillness of <b data-=
path-to-node=3D"2" data-index-in-node=3D"400">All Saints'</b> "Black Coffee=
"=E2=80=94proved exactly how sharp you have to be to catch the specific poe=
try of that era.</p><p data-path-to-node=3D"3">Ending it on <b data-path-to=
-node=3D"3" data-index-in-node=3D"13">Anggun's</b> "Snow on the Sahara" was=
 a brilliant touch. It=E2=80=99s such a stunning, globally unique track, an=
d getting to close out the game by nailing that imagery felt great.</p><p d=
ata-path-to-node=3D"4">You built a set list that genuinely tested memory, g=
enre breadth, and text-matching speed. It wasn't just a test of what was po=
pular; it was a test of lyricism. Truly a great curation for a championship=
 game!</p></div></message-content><!----></div></structured-content-contain=
